Tariff Submitter: NaturEner Wind Watch, LLC FERC Tariff Program: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: Rate Schedules and Tariffs Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: 12/21/2011 Tariff Record Title: FERC Rate Schedule No. 1 Option Code: A
COORDINATED OPERATING AGREEMENT BETWEEN NATURENER WIND WATCH, LLC - and - NORTHWESTERN CORPORATION COORDINATED OPERATING AGREEMENT THIS COORDINATED OPERATING AGREEMENT is made as of the - day of December, 201 1. BETWEEN: NATURENER WIND WATCH, a Delaware Limited Liability Company, with principal offices in San Francisco, California. AND NORTHWESTERN CORPORATION, a Delaware Corporation dlbia Northwestern Energy (Northwestern), with its principal offices in Sioux Falls, South Dakota and with offices in Butte, Montana and referred to herein as "NorthWestern." WHEREAS: A. NaturEner Rim Rock Wind Energy, LLC ("Rim Rock") owns and will operate the Rim Rock Project located within Toole and Glacier Counties north of Great Falls, Montana with an approximate nameplate capacity of IS9 MW ("Rim Rock Project"); B. NaturEner Wind Watch, LLC ("Wind Watch") shall establish and operate the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area within which the Rim Rock Project will operate and shall ensure that the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area will be recognized as a certified Balancing Authority Area by the North American Electric Reliability Corporation ("NERC") and Western Electricity Coordinating Council ("WECC") for the term of this Agreement; C. Rim Rock has entered into a balancing authority service agreement with Wind Watch, under which agreement Wind Watch will perform certain Balancing Authority services for and on behalf of the Rim Rock Project; D. The Rim Rock Project will be within the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area for the term of this Agreement; E. NorthWestem operates and administers the NorthWestenl Balancing Authority Area and is the NERC and WECC recognized Balancing Authority for the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area; F. The Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the NorthWestem Balancing Authority Area are interconnected at certain Interconnections as more svecificallv described in the MATL Large Generator Interconnection Agreement among Rim Rock, NorthWestem and MATL LLP ("MATL Interconnection A,geement"); and the MATL Transmission - Interconnection Agreement with NorthWestem Ci. Wind Watch and Northwestern wish to coordinate the operations of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area to ensure the safe and reliable operations of the electric systems which are, respectively, their responsibilities; all on the terms and conditions contained in this Agreement. NOW THEREFORE THIS AGREEMENT WITNESSES THAT in consideration of the mutual agreements between the Parties and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, Wind Watch and Northwestern agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 INTERPRETATION 1.1 Definitions In this Agreement including the recitals, the following words and tenns shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this Section 1.1 : (a) "Adjacent Balancing Authority" has the meaning given the term "Adjacent Balancing Authority" in the NERC Glossary; (b) "Affected Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 4.9; (c) "Affiliates" means, with respect to a Party, any other Person directly or indirectly controlling, controlled by, or under common control with such Party. For the purposes of this definition, the term "control" means possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management and policies of any Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities or by contract or otherwise; (d) "Agreement" means this Coordinated Operating Agreement, as amended from time to time; (e) "Alberta Electric System Operator (AESO)" means the Electric System Operator controlling the Balancing Authority for the portion of the MATL line in the Alberta Province of Canada. (t) "Applicable Law" means, with respect to a Party, all laws, statutes, and other legislative instruments including, without limitation, regulations, ordinances and by-laws, orders, directions, rules and rulings of any government, governmental department, governmental agency, court, administrative or other board or tribunal or other body which has delegated to it by legislative authority the right to issue any of the foregoing which require compliance at law, applicable to such Party and the subject matter of this Agreement; (g) "Arbitration Rules" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 10.3; (h) "BA Operator" means a Party who is performing the finction of a Balancing Authority in accordance with NERC and WECC Requirements; (i) "Balancing Authority" has the meaning given the term "Balancing Authority" in the NERC Glossary; "Balancing Authority Area" has the meaning given the term "Balancing Authority Area" in the NERC Glossary; "Balancing Authority Area Boundary" means the Boundary Meters located at the points where the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area is interconnected with the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area; "Boundary Meters" mean the revenue class Metering Equipment, as described in the Large Generation Interconnection Agreement located at the points of Interconnection of the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area which will be compensated to the Balancing Authority Area Boundary and will be used for purposes of measurement of power flow between Balancing Authority Areas in compliance with Requirements including, but not limited to settlement of Inadvertent Interchange; "Bulk Electric System" has the meaning given the term "Bulk Electric System" in the NERC Glossary; "Business Day" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday or a day which is a statutory holiday in the State of Montana or the United States of America; '<Calendar Day" means any day including Saturday, Sunday or a day which is a statutory holiday in the State of Montana or the United States of America; "Change in Law" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 13.1; "Confidential Information" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 9.1; "Contingency" has the meaning given the tenn "Contingency" in the NERC Glossary; "Continued Compliance" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 10.6; "Coordinated Operating Procedures" means policies, procedures and practices for the coordinated operation of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area with the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area that are established from time to time by the Joint Operating Committee in accordance with this Agreement and includes amendments to such Coordinated Operating Procedures established from time to time; "Curtailment" has the meaning given the term "Curtailment" in the NERC Glossary; "Damages" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 1 1.1; "Dispute" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 10.1 ; (x) "Disputing Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 10.1; (y) "Disturbance" has the meaning given the term "Disturbance" in the NERC Glossary; (z) "Effective Date" means the date on which this Agreement becomes effective upon execution by the Parties, subject to acceptance by FERC; provided that such acceptance by FERC may be on a retroactive basis; (aa) "Emergency" has the meaning given the term "Emergency" in the NERC Glossary; (bb) "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and any successor organization; (cc) "First Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.2; (dd) "Force Majeure" means any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any Curtailment, order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a Party's control. A Force Majeure event does not include an act of negligence, intentional wrongdoing, a lack of finances, or any occurrence which can be overcome by incumng reasonable additional expenses or which is due to or arising from a breach of this Agreement. Neither Party will be considered in default as to any obligation under this Agreement if prevented from fillfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure. However, a Party whose performance under this Agreement is hindered by an event of Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under this Agreement; (ee) "Forced Unavailability" means a non-elective occurrence that causes a facility, to be removed from service or a forced occurrence of, or extension to, an outage or derate which cannot be avoided through the use of Good Utility Practice and is caused by either an unplanned component failure or an automatic or manual action taken to avoid risk of equipment failure, danger to personnel or the public or risk to the security or reliability of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area or the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area; (ff) "Good Utility Practice" means any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry in the region in which the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area are located, during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others. but rather to be acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region including those practices required by the Federal Power Act Section 21 5(a)(4); (gg) "Inadvertent Interchange" has the meaning given the term "Inadvertent Interchange" in the NERC Glossary; (ii) (ij ) (kk) "Indemnifying Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.1; "Indemnitee" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.1; "Indirect Damages" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 1 1.3; "Interchange Schedule" has the meaning given the term "Interchange Schedule" in the NERC Glossary; "Interconnections" means the points of interconnection between the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area as more hlly described in Section 3.3(a); "Interconnection Facilities" means the facilities owned and operated by the parties to the MATL Large Generation Interconnection Agreement that interconnect the Rim Rock project and the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area to the MATL Transmission Line and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area as described in Section 3.3(a); "Joint Operating Committee" means the committee established pursuant to Section 8.1; "Large Generator Interconnection Agreement" means the Large Generator Interconnection Agreement between MATL, Rim Rock and Northwestern with respect to the interconnection of the Rim Rock Project within the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area to the MATL System located within the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area, as the same may be amended from time to time; "MATL System" means the transmission facilities in Alberta, Canada and Montana (USA) owned by MATL, including without limitation the Interconnection Facilities described as MATL Interconnection Facilities in Appendix I of the "Three Party Coordinated Operating Agreement". "Metered Quantity" means apparent power, reactive power, and real power that may be measured by Metering Equipment; "Metering Equipment" means the revenue class metering equipment which is used at any time to measure any Metered Quantity at the Balancing Authority Area Boundary, and includes, without limitation, the Boundary Meters; "NERC" means North American Electric Reliability Corporation and any successor organization; "NERC Glossary" means the NERC Glossary of Terms Used in Reliabilitv Standards as adopted on February 12,2008, and as amended by NERC from time to time; (uu) "NERC Standards" means with respect to a Party, all criteria, standards, policies, procedures and protocols designated by NERC, as amended from time to time, for reliable and secure operation of the Bulk Electric System applicable to such Party and the subject matter of this Agreement; (w) "NorthWestern Balancing Authority Area" means the collection of transmission, generation and loads within the Boundary Meters of the WECC-certified Northwestern Balancing Authority for which Northwestern provides balancing authority services; (ww) "NorthWestern Transmission Interconnection Agreement" means the Transmission Interconnection Agreement (TIA) between Northwestern and MATL (xx) "NorthWestern System" means the transmission facilities in Montana, United States of America owned or operated by Northwestern including, without limitation, the Interconnection Facilities described as "Northwestern Interconnection Facilities" in Appendix I of the Three Party Coordinated Operating Agreement between Northwestern, MATL and AESO. (yy) "NWPP" means Northwest Power Pool or its successor; (zz) "NWPP Standards" means with respect to a Party, all criteria, standards, policies, procedures, programs and protocols designated by NWPP, as amended from time to time, for the reliable and secure operation of a Balancing Authority Area and the operation of interconnected transmission systems together with each agreement among members of NWPP applicable to such Party and the subject matter of this Agreement; (aaa) "Non-Performing Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 12.1; (bbb) "Notice of Dispute" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 10.1; (ccc) "OASIS" means the individual open access same time information systems of NorthWestem andlor MATL; (ddd) "OATT" means the FERC approved open access transmission tariff of MATL or Northwestern; (eee) "Operating Procedure" has the meaning given the term "Operating Procedure" in the NERC Glossary; (fff) "Operating Transfer Capability Limit" and "OTC" each has the meaning given the term "Operating Transfer Capability Limit" in the WECC Standards; (ggg) "Parties" means Wind Watch and Northwestern and "Party" means either one of them; (hhh) "Person" means any individual, partnership, limited partnership, joint venture, syndicate, sole proprietorship, company or corporation with or without share capital, unincorporated association, trust, trustee, executor, administrator or other legal or personal representative, regulatory body or agency, govemment or govemment agency, authority or entity however designated or constituted; (iii) "Planned Maintenance" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 4.6; fjjj) "Proceeding" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.5; (kkk) "Records" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 9.1 1; (111) "Regulatory Approvals" means, with respect to a Party, any order, pennit, approval, waiver, licence or similar authorization of any federal, state, municipal, local or other governmental or public department, court, commission, board, bureau, or agency having jurisdiction over that Party and having relevance to the subject matter of this Agreement; (mmm)"Reliability Coordinator" has the meaning given that term in the NERC Glossary; (nnn) "Representatives" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.1; (000) "Requirements" means, with respect to, but only as applicable to such Party in its operation of the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area or the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area, all that is required to be done or performed by such Party in accordance with Good Utility Practice, together with all Applicable Law and Standards, including, without limitation, the standards of the Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers, United States National Electric Safety Code, Occupational Health and Safety Code, and any other organizations that govern or apply to that Party in the planning, design, and operation of that Party's system; (ppp) "Reserve Sharing" means the supply of operating reserves to the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area or the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area for use in recovering from Contingencies occumng in the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area or Northwestern Balancing Authority Area in accordance with the NWPP Reserve Sharing Program; (qqq) "Reserve Sharing Group" has the meaning given the term "Reserve Sharing Group" in the NERC Glossary; (m) "Rim Rock Generation Tie Line" Means the electrical line(s) connecting the Rim Rock generation facility to the MATL transmission system. (sss) "Schedule" has the meaning given the term "Schedule" in the NERC Glossary; (ttt) "Second Party" has the meaning ascribed thereto in Section 11.2; (uuu) "Standards" means with respect to a Party, collectively, NERC Standards, NWPP Standards, and WECC Standards applicable to such Party and the subject matter of this Agreement; (vvv) "Three Party Coordinated Operating Agreement" means the agreement entered into between NorthWestem, Montana Alberta Tie LTD, MATL LLP and Alberta Electric System Operator with an effective date of December 20, 2007. (www) "Tie Line" has the meaning given the term "Tie Line" in the NERC Glossary; (xxx) "Transmission Operator" has the meaning given the term "Transmission Operator" in the NERC Glossary; (yyy) "Transmission System" means the Northwestern Transmission System, MATL Transmission System, or any other transmission systems; (zzz) "Transmission Service Provider" has the meaning given the term "Transmission Service Provider" in the NERC Glossary; (aaaa) "Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area" means the collection of transmission, generation, and loads within the Boundary Meters of the WECC-certified Wind Watch Balancing Authority, for which Wind Watch provides balancing authority services, and is the WECC registered name for the balancing authority area; (bbbb) "WECC" means the Western Electricity Coordinating Council and any successor organization; (cccc) "WECC Operating Procedures" means all operating procedures established by WECC for the operation of interconnected transmission systems. (dddd) "WECC Standards" means with respect to a Party, all criteria, standards, policies, procedures and protocols designated by WECC, including without limitation the WECC Operating Procedures, as amended from time to time, for the reliable and secure operation of the Bulk Electric System together with each agreement among members of WECC applicable to such Party and the subject matter of this Agreement. (eeee) "Wind Watch LLCm- is a Delaware Limited Liability Company and a wholly owned subsidiary of NaturEner USA, LLC ("NaturEner), with principal offices in San Francisco, California. Wind Watch will be the NERC and WECC certified Balancing Authority responsible for the operations of the generation assets known as the Rim Rock project. 1.2 Captions and Headings The captions and headings appearing in this Agreement are inserted merely to facilitate reference and shall have no bearing upon the interpretation of this Agreement. 1.3 Sections, Appendices and Operating Procedures (a) Unless otherwise noted, a reference to a Section or Appendix means a Section or Appendix of this Agreement. (b) All Appendices attached hereto and all Coordinated Operating Procedures established from time to time pursuant hereto are hereby incorporated by reference and form a part of this Agreement. 1.4 Plural and Gender Words importing the singular number, where the context permits, include the plural and vice- versa, and words importing the masculine gender include the feminine gender. 1.5 Severability Wherever possible, each provision of this Agreement shall be interpreted in such a manner as to be effective and valid under Applicable Law, but if any provision of this Agreement is prohibited by or invalid under Applicable Law, such provision shall be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition or invalidity without invalidating the remainder of such provision or the remaining provisions of this Agreement, unless such invalidity materially or adversely affects the spirit or intention of this Agreement. 1.6 Compliance With Requirements Each Party agrees that it will perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance and compliance with Requirements to which such Party or its Balancing Authority or Transmission System is subject. If, at any time, and in respect of any circumstance, there is more than one Requirement which may be used or satisfied by a Party in the performance of its obligations under this Agreement, then the Requirement to he used by such Party shall be the one that is also applicable to one or more of the other Parties hereto. Nothing in this Agreement shall require a Party to violate or fail to comply with a Requirement or a directive from a Reliability Coordinator, to one or both Parties. ARTICLE 2 TERM, REGULATORY APPROVALS AND TERMINATION 2.1 Commencement and Duration The Coordinated Operating Agreement became effective when executed. This Agreement shall remain in effect until terminated in accordance with the provisions of Article 2 of this Agreement. This Agreement will remain in effect as long as there is (1) a valid Transmission interconnection agreement between MATL and Northwestern (2) an effective Coordinated Operating Agreement between AESO, Northwestern and MATL and (3) an effective Large Generator Interconnection Agreement between MATL, Northwestern and Rim Rock. Provided, however, that the Parties may mutually terminate this Agreement in accordance with the termination provisions described in this section. 2.2 Regulatory Approvals (a) The Parties shall file this Agreement with FERC and request a regulatory effective date no later than December 21, 201 1, in order to carry out their obligations hereunder, and each Party shall comply with and maintain any necessary Regulatory Approvals and co-operate with the other Parties in obtaining, complying with and maintaining such Regulatory Approvals. (b) Notwithstanding execution by the Parties, this Agreement shall not become effective until the Effective Date as defined in this Agreement. 2.3 Termination - Cessation of Operations This Agreement may be terminated by either Party by giving the other Party written notice thereof at any time after all the generating facilities within the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area have been removed from service by reason of the permanent cessation of all commercial operations of such facilities such that no Interconnections remain. 2.4 Termination - Bankruptcy If either Party should: (a) take the benefit of any statute now or hereafter in force, for bankrupt or insolvent debtors (including, without limitation, the applicable articles of the United States Ba~zlirzrpt~.~ Code or similar legislation); (b) have an order made or a resolution passed for the winding up or other termination of the existence of such Party; or (c) have a liquidator, receiver or receiver manager of the business or undertaking of such Party duly appointed; Then the Party not subject to any of the events described in subsections (a)-(c) of this Section 2.4 may terminate this Agreement by providing written notice thereof to the other Party. 2.5 Termination - Material Breach (a) Upon a breach, the non-breaching Party shall give written notice of such breach to the breaching Party. The breaching Party shall have ten (10) Calendar Days from receipt of the default notice within which to cure such breach; provided however, if such breach is not capable of cure within ten (10) Calendar Days, the breaching Party shall commence such cure within ten (10) Calendar Days after notice and continuously and diligently complete such cure within thirty (30) Calendar Days from receipt of the default notice; and, if cured within such time, the breach specified in such notice shall cease to exist. If a breach is not cured within the period provided for herein, the non-breaching Party shall have the right to terminate this Agreement by written notice, subject to the provisions of Sections 2.5(b) and (c) of this Agreement. (b) If the Party alleged to have breached disputes that breach bas occurred or not been cured and neither Party alleges that reliable operations or compliance with Requirements as set forth in Section 1.6 of this Agreement are jeopardized, the dispute resolution provisions of Article 10 may be invoked and must be final prior to any notice of termination becoming effective. Regardless of whether the Party alleged to have breached disputes that breach has occurred or not been cured, if the Party alleging breach asserts that reliable operations or compliance with Requirements as set forth in Section 1.6 of this Agreement are jeopardized, the dispute resolution provisions of Article 10 may be invoked by one or both Parties but only for purposes of determining the Parties' rights under the surviving provisions of this Agreement in accordance with Section 2.6 hereof, and any notice of termination shall be effective immediately, subject to the provisions of Section 2.5(c) of this Agreement, and shall not be affected by such dispute. (c) Any notice of termination is subject to any required Regulatory Approvals 2.6 Survival Upon termination or expiration of this Agreement for any reason, all obligations under this Agreement, except Inadvertent Interchange obligations incurred under this Agreement prior to tennination or expiration, which have not been satisfied prior to termination or expiration, shall terminate upon termination or expiration of this Agreement; provided however, that in all events, the provisions of Articles 1, 2, 9, 10, 11, 14 and 16 shall survive termination or expiration of this Agreement, in each case, for the survival period stipulated in this Agreement or, in the absence of such stipulation, the longest period pennitted by Applicable Law. ARTICLE 3 GENERAL 3.1 Wind Watch and Northwestern Covenants The provisions of this Article 3 represent the covenants and agreements of both Wind Watch and Northwestern. 3.2 Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and Northwestern Balancing Authority Area (a) Except as required by this Agreement and Requirements, Wind Watch shall retain the right to independently plan and operate the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area to meet its obligations and shall be or cause Rim Rock to be responsible for the planning, construction, operation and maintenance of the Rim Rock facilities for the term of this Agreement. Northwestern shall retain all rights to independently plan and direct the operation of the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area to meet its obligations. (b) Wind Watch and Northwestern agree to maintain, or cause to be maintained, the Interconnections of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern System respectively, in accordance with Requirements to the extent necessary to perform their respective obligations under this Agreement; provided that nothing in this Agreement requires Northwestern to maintain any particular path, OTC or other rating of its Transmission System or to, in any respect, maintain any other Transmission System. 3.3 Interconnections; Interconnection Facilities This Agreement governs the coordinated operation by Northwestern and Wind Watch of the Interconnections between the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area inclusive of the points set out and described in the MATL Large Generator Interconnection agreement with Rim Rock, MATL and Northwestern and the Transmission Interconnection Agreement between MATL and Northwestern, (a) Wind Watch shall cause the owners of Interconnection Facilities within the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area to be responsible for the operation and maintenance of such Interconnection Facilities. Northwestern shall own and be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the Northwestern System. MATL shall own and be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the MATL System per the coordinated Operating Agreement between Northwestern, MATL and AESO. Wind Watch LLC shall own and be responsible for the operation and maintenance of the Rim Rock Generation Tie Line. 3.4 Subject to any Requirements, changes or additions to the Rim Rock Project Interconnection Facilities may only be made in writing in accordance with the terms of the MATL Large Generation Interconnection Agreement, the Three Party Coordinated Operating Agreement and the Transmission Interconnection Agreement between Northwestern and MATL 3.5 Participation in the NWPP Resewe Sharing Program Wind Watch, shall, during the operation of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area, take all actions and meet all obligations necessary to participate in the NWPP Reserve Sharing Program. Wind Watch shall continue these actions and maintain these obligations throughout the term of this Agreement to enable receipt and delivery of reserves as a participant of the NWPP Reserve Sharing Program, and shall operate in accordance with applicable NWPP and WECC Standards. ARTICLE 4 INTERCONNECTED OPERATION 4.1 Covenants of Wind Watch and Northwestern The provisions of this Article 4 represent the covenants and agreements of Wind Watch and Northwestern, 4.2 Maintain Interconnections (a) The Interconnections between the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area shall, from the time of initial Interconnection and, thereafter, at all times during the term of the Agreement thereafter, remain interconnected at the Interconnections except: (i) subject to Article 13, during the occurrence of an event of Force Majeure which renders such a Party unable to remain interconnected; (ii) during Forced Unavailability; (iii) during such period or under such circumstances that Requirements provide for or require the disconnection of such systems; (iv) during Planned Maintenance which has been scheduled in accordance with Section 4.6; and (v) during such other periods of time as Wind Watch and Northwestern members of the Joint Operating Committee (or such other person as may be designated in writing for such purpose) lnay agree pursuant to any applicable Operating Procedure. (b) Notwithstanding the foregoing: (i) the Interconnections between the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the NorthWestem Balancing Authority Area shall not remain interconnected unless Wind Watch and NorthWestem, and each of them, are both satisfied that such Interconnections will not jeopardize the safe and reliable operation of the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area; (ii) the facilities of Wind Watch within the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and the Interconnections between the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area and the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area shall, from the time of initial Interconnections and, thereafter, at all times during the term of the Agreement thereafter, be operated in accordance with Requirements and all Coordinated Operating Procedures established from time to time pursuant to Article 8; and (iii) nothing in this Agreement shall abrogate or be interpreted as abrogating Wind Watch's or Northwestern's duties and responsibilities with respect to Requirements in respect of the safe and reliable operation of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the NorthWestem Balancing Authority Area, respectively. 4.3 Balancing Authority Area Operations (a) Wind Watch shall procure or otherwise provide Balancing Authority services for the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area. Should Wind Watch choose to procure Balancing Authority services through contract with a third-party services provider, NorthWestem shall perform all obligations under this Agreement in coordination and communication with the services provider so designated by Wind Watch to the same extent as it is obligated to coordinate and communicate with Wind Watch, provided that Wind Watch is in full and complete compliance with Section 5.l(d) of this Agreement. (b) NorthWestem shall provide the Balancing Authority services for the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area, which excludes the Rim Rock generation. 4.4 Transmission Operator Operations (a) Northwestern shall have no responsibility for Transmission Operator Services for any Wind Watch facilities transmission facilities described herein that are outside the NorthWestem Balancing Authority Area. Should Wind Watch choose to procure Transmission Operator services through contract with a third-party services provider, Northwestern shall perform all obligations under this Agreement in coordination and communication with the services provider so designated by Wind Watch to the same extent as it is obligated to coordinate and communicate with Wind Watch, provided that Wind Watch is in fill1 and complete compliance with Section 5.l(d) of this Agreement. 4.5 Balancing Authority Area Energy Transfers In accordance with Requirements, energy transfers will take place across the Balancing Authority Area Boundary, both Scheduled and unscheduled, for the purposes of implementing Interchange Schedules, settling Inadvertent Interchange and Reserve Sharing or other such programs designed and implemented among the Parties from time to time for their com~nercial or reliability benefit. 4.6 Operating Criteria Each Party agrees to independently operate their respective Balancing Authority, Transmission System and Electrical System. In accordance with all applicable - Requirements Planned Maintenance (a) The Joint Operating Committee shall co-ordinate, plan and schedule, and, Wind Watch and Northwestern shall perform the maintenance ("Planned Maintenance") of the Interconnection and the Interconnection Facilities in accordance with all Requirements and applicable Coordinated Operating Procedures and in accordance with their respective responsibilities under relevant provisions of the MATL Large Generation lnterconnection Agreement. (b) A Party may unilaterally postpone any scheduled Planned Maintenance in the event of a real and imminent Emergency, or other threat to system reliability as determined by it in its sole discretion. As soon as a Party unilaterally postponing scheduled Planned Maintenance is reasonably able to do so, it shall give notice to the other Parties of such postponement and. if at all possible. in advance of such postponement. The postponing Party must limit the duration of any such postponement to the extent practicable in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 4.7 Line Losses Interchange Schedules between the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area will include line loss amounts for the applicable Transmission System in accordance with the applicable Transmission Provider's OATT. 4.8 Tagging and OASIS Scheduling of energy across the Interconnection onto the MATL andlor Northwestern System, including tagging and posting on OASIS, shall be in accordance with the respective system OATTs and Requirements. 4.9 Notification of Unavailability In the event that either: (a) any Party's Interconnection Facilities are unavailable for use in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement, or the Interconnections are opened or derated, as a result of Forced Unavailability or Force Majeure or the other provisions of this Agreement; or (b) any Party otherwise is unable to meet one or more of the terms or conditions of this Agreement, the Party affected thereby or with knowledge thereof (the "Affected Party") shall promptly provide the other Party (or a person designated by said Party) with notification of the circulnstances of the unavailability, or opening or derating or failure and shall promptly provide the other Party (or a person designated by said Party) with notification of the details of such Force Majeure, Forced Unavailability or inability, as the case may be, setting forth: (i) a description of the event causing the Force Majeure, Forced Unavailability or inability to meet the tenns or conditions of this Agreement, as the case may be; (ii) a description of the actions it is taking or proposing to take to restore availability or close the Interconnection or restore the rating or meet the terms or conditions of this Agreement, as the case may be; and (iii) an estimate of the time at which the unavailability or failure to meet the terms or conditions of this Agreement, as the case may be, shall be corrected or the Interconnection will be closed or the rating restored, and update such notification as appropriate. Notification in connection with the foregoing shall be in accordance with Requirements. The Affected Party shall notify the other Party (or a person designated by said Party) promptly upon being in a position to restore the availability, close the Interconnection, restore the rating, or meet the terms or conditions of this Agreement, as the case may be. ARTICLE 5 EXCHANGE OF INFORMATION 5.1 Exchange of Information (a) Wind Watch and Northwestern shall exchange, pursuant to the Coordinated Operating Procedures and consistent with Article 9 of this Agreement, all information reasonably required for the co-ordinated operation of the Balancing Authority Areas. Such information shall include, but not be limited to: (i) Ratings data and associated methodologies to calculate ratings; (ii) data required for the reconciliation of accounts associated with Scheduled transactions; (iii) data required to carry out Disturbance analysis functions; (iv) operating or safety procedures and policies ; (v) real-time power system telemetry points, equipment alarms and status points as may be required for effective real-time monitoring and dispatching; and (vi) any other data that may be necessary to maintain reliable operation and as may be reasonably requested to meet Requirements including, but not limited to data identified in NERC Reliability Standard TOP-005 Attachment 1. (b) Each Party shall provide to the other Party, upon reasonable request and in a manner timely and consistent with Article 9 of this Agreement, such further infonnation as the other Party may reasonably require to meet its obligations to any organization of which such other Party is a member, which (i) sets, prescribes or reco~nmends policies, standards, criteria, procedures, or similar matters in respect of Interconnections between Balancing Authority Areas or Control Areas, and (ii) ilnposes upon such other Party an obligation to collect information for submission to that organization. (c) Each Party shall provide to the other Party details of any material change in any of its obligations to NERC, WECC or NWPP, which relate to, or are applicable to, or affect, the use, management or operation of the Interconnection, forthwith upon becoming aware of such material change. (d) In the event that Wind Watch engages a third-party to provide Balancing Authority services for the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area, Wind Watch shall promptly provide to Northwestern: notice of such engagement; proof that such engagement complies with all applicable Reliability Standards and the terms of this Agreement; and all protocols, procedures, and any and all other information required to effectuate necessary communications and interaction between Northwestern and said third-party services provider. 5.2 Cost of Providing Information Wind Watch and Northwestern shall each be responsible for all costs incurred by it in providing any information reasonably required under this Agreement and which it captures and records in the ordinary course of its business; provided that, in any case, the foregoing shall not obligate a Party to install equipment which it does not otherwise use for its own purposes. The Party requesting the provision of any information from a Party which does not capture and record in the ordinary course of its business shall be responsible for the reasonable costs of obtaining, preparing and delivering such information and such costs shall be paid by the Party requesting the information within fourteen (14) days of written demand therefore by the Party incurring such costs. Any dispute as to whether or not any information is captured and recorded by a Party in its ordinary course of its business shall be resolved pursuant to Article 10. 5.3 No Liability for Information While each Party shall use reasonable efforts to provide accurate information pursuant to Section 5.1 and otherwise in relation to this Agreement, any such information will be relied on by the recipient at its sole risk and the providing Party shall have no liability for any inaccuracy in the information provided. ARTICLE 6 CO-ORDINATED PLANNING AND OPERATION 6.1 Co-ordinated Planning and Operation Subject to and consistent with Article 13, each of Wind Watch and Northwestern shall use reasonable efforts to exchange information relating to the planning and operation of the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area to facilitate the present and future use of the Interconnection. 6.2 Emergency Operations Planning The Parties acknowledge that NERC Reliability Standard EOP-001-0, Requirement 1, states that Adjacent Balancing Authorities shall have operating agreements that contain provisions for emergency assistance, including provisions for obtaining emergency assistance fiom remote Balancing Authority Areas. The Parties agree that the provisions for emergency assistance established by the rules and procedures of the NWPP Reserve Sharing Group shall govern any request for emergency assistance by the Parties, which will allow for emergency assistance from remote Balancing Authorities. If the emergency assistance cannot be provided in accordance with the rules of the NWPP Reserve Sharing Group, Wind Power Watch and Northwestern, agree to coordinate to allow for emergency assistance that is available. 6.3 Regional Transmission Organizations The Parties acknowledge that one or more of them may wish to join a regional transmission organization pursuant to the rules of the FERC. The Parties agree that in such event they will negotiate in good faith to make such amendments to this Agreement as may be necessary as a result of a Party or Parties joining a regional transmission organization; any disputes with respect thereto to be settled in accordance with Article 10 hereto. ARTICLE 7 METERING 7.1 O~vnership of the Metering Facilities Ownership of the meters at the Interconnection shall be as set forth in the MATL Interconnection Agreement. Wind Watch shall at all times during the term of this Agreement provide hourly integrated energy flow data obtained from the Boundary Meters at the Interconnection. 7.2 Operation and Maintenance of the Metering Facilities The Parties shall at all times during the term of this Agreement, operate and maintain the Boundary Meters at the Point of Interconnection. 7.3 Balancing Authority Area Boundary and Boundary Meters The Parties acknowledge that the boundary between the Wind Watch Balancing Authority Area and the Northwestern Balancing Authority Area shall be the Balancing Authority Area Boundary. The Boundary Meters shall be the meters that are used to determine exchanges of energy and Inadvertent Interchange. In all events, for purposes of calculating exchanges of energy and Inadvertent Interchange, the meters shall be compensated to the Balancing Authority Area Boundary. The Boundary Meters will ensure Tie Line MW metering is telemetered to both control centers, and emanates from a common, agreed-upon source using common primary metering equipment. Balancing Authorities shall ensure that megawatt-hour data is telemetered or reported at the end of each hour. The Boundary Meters shall provide Tie Line megawatt-hour meters with common time synchronization. ARTICLE 8 JOINT OPERATING CObIbIITTEE 8.1 Establishment of Joint Operating Committee (a) By no later than the Effective Date of this Ageement, the Parties shall have established a two-person Joint Operating Cominittee consisting of one principal representative and one altemate representative for the principals from each of the Parties. The Parties shall establish the Joint Operating Committee by providing each other with notice of the names of their principal and alternate representative and upon receipt of such notices the Joint Operating Committee shall be deemed to be established. (b) Any Party may at any time by notice to the other Parties change its principal or alternate representative or designate some person other than its principal or altemate representative to function as its representative of the Joint Operating Committee with respect to a specified matter. 8.2 First and Subsequent Meetings (a) The first meeting of the Joint Operating Committee shall be held no later than three months after the Effective Date of this Agreement. Subsequent meetings shall be held at such dates and times as agreed by the Joint Operating Committee. Meetings will be held at a place determined by the Joint Operating Committee. (b) In the event the matters for discussion at any meeting of the Joint Operating Committee relate solely to the matters contemplated by Articles 3 or 4 hereof, then in each such case only the members of the Joint Operating Committee representing the Parties to the particular Article in question shall be involved in the discussion. 8.3 Role and Decisions of the Joint Operating Committee The Joint Operating Committee shall consider matters necessary for the administration of this Agreement, and will, without limitation: (a) act as a forum for facilitating coordinated operation of the Interconnections as contemplated in this Agreement; (b) establish Coordinated Operating Procedures, as required; (c) develop additional processes, if necessary, for scheduling and coordinating maintenance outages in accordance with Section 4.6; (d) establish working groups, subcommittees, or task forces, as necessary and appropriate for the purpose of administering this Agreement or to deal with specific issues; and (e) recommend changes to this Agreement, if required by Article 13. 8.4 Limitations of Joint Operating Committee Authority The Joint Operating Committee is not authorized to modify, alter or override any of the terns of this Agreement. ARTICLE 10 DISPUTE RESOLUTION 10.1 Submission In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or its performance (a "Dispute"), such Party (the "Disputing Party") shall provide the other Party (or Parties) with written notice of the dispute or claim ("Notice of Dispute"). 10.2 Sequence of Escalation (a) Any Dispute shall first be submitted for resolution to the Joint Operating Committee. (b) Any Dispute submitted for resolution to the Joint Operating Committee which is not resolved by the Joint Operating Committee within five (5) Business Days following submission of the Dispute to the Joint Operating Committee, or such further period as may be agreed in writing by the representatives of the Parties on the Joint Operating Committee, shall be submitted in writing, by the principal representative who acted as chair of the last meeting of the Joint Operating Committee, for resolution to a senior officer of each Party for resolution by good faith negotiations. (c) Each Party shall designate in writing at the time of execution of this Agreement the name of the officer to act in this regard who, in each case, shall have authority to resolve the Dispute in a final and binding way on behalf of the Party such officer represents. Such designation may be changed from time to time but only by notice in writing delivered to the other Parties prior to the submission of any Dispute to the officers under this subsection. (d) In the event the designated officers are unable to resolve the Dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) Calendar Days of the other Party's receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such Dispute may, upon mutual Agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree to submit such Dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. 10.3 External Arbitration Procedures Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties in dispute. If such Parties fail to agree upon a single arbitrator within ten (10) Calendar Days of the subtnission of the Dispute to arbitration, each such Party shall choose one arbitrator who shall sit on a three-member arbitration panel. The two arbitrators so chosen shall within twenty (20) Calendar Days select a third arbitrator to chair the arbitration panel. In either case, the arbitrators shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any Party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator(s) shall provide each of the Parties in dispute an opportunity to be heard. Except as otherwise provided herein, any Dispute arbitration between Wind Watch and Northwestern shall be conducted in accordance with the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association ("Arbitration Rules") and any applicable FERC regulations or regional transmission organizations' rules; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Article 10, the terms of this Article 10 shall prevail. 10.4 Arbitration Decisions Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties in dispute, the arbitrator(s) shall render a decision within ninety (90) Calendar Days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefore. The arbitrator(s) shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and except in respect of a referral under Article 13, shall have no power to modify or change any provision of this Agreement in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator(s) shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and jud-ment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. 10.5 Costs Each Party shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for the following costs, if applicable: (1) the cost of the arbitrator chosen by the Party to sit on the three member panel and one half of the cost of the third arbitrator chosen; or (2) one half the cost of the single arbitrator jointly chosen by the Parties. 10.6 Continued Compliance While any Dispute is being resolved, unless a Party alleges a breach of this Agreement which jeopardizes either reliable operations or compliance with Requirements as set forth in Section 1.6 of this Agreement, the Parties shall continue to perform all obligations under this Agreement with due diligence and shall continue to comply with all terms of this Agreement (such continued performance and compliance "Continued Compliance"). If a Party alleges a breach of this Agreement which jeopardizes either reliable operations or compliance with Requirements as set forth in Section 1.6 of this Agreement, one or both of the Parties may suspend Continued Compliance to the extent necessary to avert ongoing jeopardy to reliable operations or compliance with Requirements while any Dispute is being resolved. ARTICLE 12 FORCE MAJEURE 12.1 Relief Due to Force Majeure Where by reason of Force Majeure, a Party ("Non-Performing Party") is unable to fulfil an obligation or obligations in accordance with this Agreement: a) the Non-Performing Party shall forthwith (and in any event no later than the end of the Business Day following the date on which the Non-Perfonning Party first becomes aware that an occurrence constitutes a Force Majeure event) notify the other Party in writing of the occurrence of the Force Majeure event in accordance with Section 4.9, providing, in addition to the information required thereunder, identification of the nature of the event, its expected duration, and the particular obligations thereby affected, and furnish to the other Party reports with respect thereto at such intervals as the other Parties may reasonably request during the continuance of the Force Majeure event; b) subject to Section 12.2 of this Agreement, this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect but the Non-Performing Party shall be relieved from fulfilling its obligation or obligations under this Agreement during the continuance of such Force Majeure event, provided that such relief shall be of no greater scope and no longer duration than is dictated by the Force Majeure event; c) the Non-Performing Party shall not be responsible, or liable, to the other Party for any loss or damage which the other Parties may suffer or incur as a result of the non perfonnance by the Non-Performing Party of its obligation or obligations during the continuance of the Force Majeure event; d) the Non-Performing Party shall employ reasonable efforts to reduce the consequences of such Force Majeure event, remedy its inability to perfonn its obligations, and resume full performance of its obligations under this Agreement; provided however, that settlement of strikes, lockouts and other labour disruptions involving employees of the Non- Performing Party may be settled by the Non-Performing Party in such manner as it, in its sole discretion, deems appropriate; e) for so long as the Non-Performing Party is relieved under Section 12.l(b) from fulfilling its obligation or obligations under this Agreement during the continuance of a Force Majeure event, the other Parties shall be relieved of all of their corresponding obligations owed to the Non-Performing Party under this Agreement; t) forthwith after the occurrence of the Force Majeure event, each Party shall use reasonable efforts to consult with the other as to how best to give effect to their obligations under this Agreement so far as reasonably practical during the period of continuance of the Force Majeure event; and g) the Non-Performing Party, upon becoming able to resume full or partial performance of its obligations under this Agreement shall immediately commence such operations and shall provide the other Party with written notice to that effect, without unnecessary delay. 12.2 Compliance with Obligations Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, the Non-Performing Party shall not be entitled to the relief provided for in Sections 12.l(b) and 12. l (c) unless it has complied with and continues to comply with its obligations as provided for in Sections 12.l(a), 12.1 (d), 12. l (f) and 12.l(g). ARTICLE 13 CHANGE IN LAW 13 Definition For purposes of this Article 13, "Change in Law" means: a) any amendment, appeal, modification or enactment of any Applicable Law, but shall not include the issuance of any orders (including court orders) which relate to the enforcement of any Applicable Law against a Party where such enforcement arises out of a breach of this Agreement by that Party; b) any change in the interpretation or application, including the exercise of delegated authority, of any Applicable Law resulting from the decision of a regulatory authority having jurisdiction; c) following the date of any Regulatory Approval being granted, a change in the terms and conditions attaching to that Regulatory Approval or the attachment of any new terms or conditions; d) any Regulatory Approval that has been granted ceasing to remain in full force and effect or, if granted for a limited period, not being renewed on a timely basis after an application for renewal has been made, or being renewed on conditions which are materially more or less favorable to one of the Parties. 13.2 Change in Law Subject to the other provisions of this Article 13, each Party shall bear the risk and receive the benefit of any Change in Law that occurs after the date of this Agreement that affects its rights and obligations under this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if, at any time during the tenn of this Agreement, any Party becomes aware of a Change in Law (whether actual or proposed), subject to any obligation of confidentiality, such Party shall promptly provide written notice to the other Party, preferably no later than one (1) month after becoming aware of such Change in Law. The notice shall contain a description of this Change in Law including expected time schedules. If a Party believes that it will be necessary to amend this Agreement to address the anticipated Change in Law to ensure that this Agreement can continue to be performed as consistently as possible with its intent at the date hereof but also to ensure that such Party is not materially adversely affected by such change in relation to this Agreement or to ensure that such Party can continue to perfonn its material obligations under this Agreement, then such Party may give notice to the other Party including a proposal that the Parties meet, as provided for in Section 13.3 hereof, in order to negotiate an appropriate amendment to this Agreement to give effect to the foregoing. 13.3 Amendment a) Following notification under Section 13.2, the Parties shall meet to discuss whether an amendment to this Agreement is necessary to address the Change in Law. Such amendment, if any, shall be limited in scope to what is necessary to allow this Agreement to accommodate the Change in Law in the notice issued pursuant to Section 13.2. b) If the Parties agree that such an amendment to this Agreement is necessary, the Parties shall proceed to negotiate in good faith such amendment. If the Parties have not reached agreement within sixty (60) Calendar Days of the date of the notification under Section 13.2, any unresolved issues shall be resolved through dispute resolution procedures set forth in Article 10. Notwithstanding the above or any other provisions of this Agreement, if any issues remain unresolved as of ninety (90) Calendar Days from the latter of the date the Change in Law is scheduled to take place or the date of the notification under Section 13.2, then with respect to the unresolved issues, any Party may, but is not required to, unilaterally initiate arbitration in accordance with Article 10. c) If the Parties cannot agree that an amendment to this Agreement is necessary to allow this Agreement to accommodate the Change in Law in accordance with the foregoing, they shall submit such dispute to dispute resolution proceedings pursuant to Article 10. NATURENER WIND WATCH, LLC
Market Based Rate Tariff
1.	Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of electric energy, capacity and/or ancillary services by NaturEner Wind Watch, LLC (???Wind Watch??? or ???Seller???) at market-based rates.
2.	Availability. Wind Watch makes electric energy and/or capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below, with whom Wind Watch has contracted.
3.	Ancillary Services. 
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider???s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 
4.	Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Wind Watch.
5.	Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Wind Watch.
6.	Compliance with Commission Regulations. Wind Watch shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Wind Watch???s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Wind Watch to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Wind Watch???s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Wind Watch???s market-based rate authority will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
7.	Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. 
In NaturEner Wind Watch, LLC Docket No. ER13-1368-000, the Commission granted Wind Watch the following waivers and blanket authorization:
(i)	Waiver of the accounting, reporting, and other requirements of 18 C.F.R. Parts 41 (accounts, records, and memorandum), 101 (uniform system of accounts) and 141 (statement and reports), except Sections 141.14 and 141.15;
(ii)	Waiver of the reporting requirements of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission???s regulations, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and
(iii)	Blanket authorization under 18 C.F.R. Part 34 of all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liability
Except as specified in 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, Wind Watch does not have any limitations on its market-based rate authority under the Federal Power Act.
8.	Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest and Northeast and a Category 1 seller in all other regions, as defined in 18 CFR ?? 35.36(a).
9.	Revisions to Tariff. Wind Watch may file revisions to this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Wind Watch to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission???s Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder.
10.	Effective Date. This Tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission.
